WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:03.510
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:03.510 --> 00:00:24.520
[ Silence ]

00:00:24.520 --> 00:00:25.820
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: Good evening.

00:00:25.820 --> 00:00:28.350
I'm Anne McLean from the
Library's concert office.

00:00:28.350 --> 00:00:29.870
With this talk, I'm delighted

00:00:29.870 --> 00:00:33.330
to be officially opening the
90th anniversary celebration

00:00:33.330 --> 00:00:35.670
of the Library's concert series.

00:00:35.670 --> 00:00:38.830
We're celebrating nine
decades of splendid concerts,

00:00:38.830 --> 00:00:41.010
a long and storied legacy.

00:00:41.010 --> 00:00:44.270
Coming up, a terrific and
very exciting 90 weeks

00:00:44.270 --> 00:00:46.820
of celebration starting tonight.

00:00:46.820 --> 00:00:48.660
We have a stunning
line-up of concerts

00:00:48.660 --> 00:00:51.780
and events reflecting our
past, and we're looking ahead

00:00:51.780 --> 00:00:54.860
to a very strong and
exhilarating future.

00:00:54.860 --> 00:00:57.930
As insiders and good
friends, you're the first

00:00:57.930 --> 00:01:00.510
to get a mini sneak
preview of our celebration

00:01:00.510 --> 00:01:03.790
which will continue
through September 2016.

00:01:03.790 --> 00:01:07.750
We have quite a lot to celebrate
including the three jewels

00:01:07.750 --> 00:01:09.050
of our series.

00:01:09.050 --> 00:01:11.710
Which are the superb
auditorium, our rare instruments,

00:01:11.710 --> 00:01:14.660
and the vast expanse of the
music division's collections.

00:01:14.660 --> 00:01:17.270
Nearly 22 million items.

00:01:17.270 --> 00:01:21.540
More than 500 commissions including
landmark works by Maurice Ravel,

00:01:21.540 --> 00:01:23.690
Bayla [phonetic] Bartaugh,
Arnold Schoenberg,

00:01:23.690 --> 00:01:26.170 position:56%
Aaron Copeland, and many, many more.

00:01:26.170 --> 00:01:30.480
Warm relationships, a theme of
this talk, and a huge roster

00:01:30.480 --> 00:01:33.790
of towering musical figures
from several generations.

00:01:33.790 --> 00:01:36.130
Plus, a very sophisticated audience

00:01:36.130 --> 00:01:39.320
which plays an important
role in our history.

00:01:39.320 --> 00:01:41.190
Among the world's national
libraries,

00:01:41.190 --> 00:01:43.860
we are unique in being
a major presenter.

00:01:43.860 --> 00:01:47.240
As the nation's oldest
federal cultural institution,

00:01:47.240 --> 00:01:49.880
the Library is also an
important actor in the realm

00:01:49.880 --> 00:01:51.500
of cultural diplomacy,

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:56.110
and our concerts very
much reflect this mission.

00:01:56.110 --> 00:01:59.400
Opus 90 seemed an appropriate
title for this talk

00:01:59.400 --> 00:02:02.600
because our founder Elizabeth
Sprague Coolidge called her work

00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:03.900
here the creation

00:02:03.900 --> 00:02:07.630
of this extraordinary
series, her Magnum Opus.

00:02:07.630 --> 00:02:10.920
It is a great work that is
still very much ongoing,

00:02:10.920 --> 00:02:13.640
evolving as our culture evolves.

00:02:13.640 --> 00:02:16.650
And it has continued to be
a great and absorbing work

00:02:16.650 --> 00:02:20.480 position:56%
for the many people fortunate enough
to have helped it live so vibrantly

00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:23.970
since its founding
almost 90 years ago.

00:02:23.970 --> 00:02:25.880
Throughout our history,

00:02:25.880 --> 00:02:28.940
the programming has been
informed by some constants.

00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:32.900
The intention to present concerts
of the highest artistic caliber,

00:02:32.900 --> 00:02:35.430
the ideal of uncompromising
integrity,

00:02:35.430 --> 00:02:39.360
and the goals of diversity
and democratic outreach.

00:02:39.360 --> 00:02:43.170
Here are some of the questions
that we'll look into in this hour.

00:02:43.170 --> 00:02:45.640
How did the Library of
Congress come to be the owner

00:02:45.640 --> 00:02:47.770
and operator of a concert series?

00:02:47.770 --> 00:02:50.200 position:56%
How have we effected the development

00:02:50.200 --> 00:02:52.290
and appreciation of
music in America?

00:02:52.290 --> 00:02:56.760
First in classical music
and later a range of genres?

00:02:56.760 --> 00:03:00.230
What's the story of the
concerts as a media presence?

00:03:00.230 --> 00:03:02.980
And, finally, how does
the visionary thinking

00:03:02.980 --> 00:03:05.830
of our predecessors inform
our strategic planning

00:03:05.830 --> 00:03:09.960
for the future while we press
forward in new directions?

00:03:13.160 --> 00:03:16.610
To answer these questions, we
naturally begin with Mrs. Coolidge.

00:03:16.610 --> 00:03:20.700
A formidable lady of great
imagination, passion, intelligence,

00:03:20.700 --> 00:03:25.710
and tremendous energy whose 150th
birthday we celebrate this season.

00:03:25.710 --> 00:03:32.270
This is an image with an early
image of her around 1902.

00:03:32.270 --> 00:03:36.400 position:56%
Still with the dramatic big hats and
if you can see the whole picture,

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:39.870
a long bustle and everything.

00:03:39.870 --> 00:03:43.070
As you'll see when we go
forward from this background,

00:03:43.070 --> 00:03:45.650
she became a very,
very modern woman.

00:03:45.650 --> 00:03:51.630
One that is still a
remarkable inspiration today.

00:03:51.630 --> 00:03:59.090
Her concept, in 1925, she
endowed the Library of Congress

00:03:59.090 --> 00:04:03.240
with our superb concert hall
and endowed a foundation

00:04:03.240 --> 00:04:06.710
to support a free chamber
music series.

00:04:06.710 --> 00:04:11.200 position:56%
Her gift was a groundbreaking public
private partnership requiring an act

00:04:11.200 --> 00:04:13.150
of Congress.

00:04:13.150 --> 00:04:15.140
This concept was radical.

00:04:15.140 --> 00:04:17.220
It was one that would
bring the nation's library

00:04:17.220 --> 00:04:19.660
to international visibility
as a presenter

00:04:19.660 --> 00:04:23.450
and establish a precedent
for future benefactors.

00:04:23.450 --> 00:04:26.120
It would raise the awareness
of chamber music in America

00:04:26.120 --> 00:04:30.860
and ensure her legacy as one of the
great music patrons of her time.

00:04:30.860 --> 00:04:34.700
She was a fine pianist
who loved chamber music.

00:04:34.700 --> 00:04:37.630
You see her in this grainy
image here with her son, Albert.

00:04:37.630 --> 00:04:41.680
She was a lifelong
student of composition

00:04:41.680 --> 00:04:43.040
and published some pieces.

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:45.460
She had one piece published
by G Shermer.

00:04:45.460 --> 00:04:49.190
That work which was a set of Mother
Goose songs was also recorded,

00:04:49.190 --> 00:04:54.080
and you can see in here a
Victor [inaudible] of that.

00:04:54.080 --> 00:04:57.390
She wrote a string quartet
and an oboe and piano sonata,

00:04:57.390 --> 00:05:01.490
a number of pieces which we have
here and have had played through

00:05:01.490 --> 00:05:03.740
and one has been performed.

00:05:03.740 --> 00:05:07.100
Had Mrs. Coolidge been from a
different social background,

00:05:07.100 --> 00:05:10.310
she very likely would have
been a professional musician.

00:05:10.310 --> 00:05:14.200
She would become a sophisticated
presenter, a true impresario

00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:17.460
with excellent taste and
the highest standards.

00:05:17.460 --> 00:05:22.080
On her arrival in Washington,
she was at 60 already well known

00:05:22.080 --> 00:05:24.950
as the founder of the
Berkshire Festival and had begun

00:05:24.950 --> 00:05:27.480
to commission a roster of
compositions that would help

00:05:27.480 --> 00:05:30.790
to shape the history
of 20th century music.

00:05:30.790 --> 00:05:34.300
Mrs. Coolidge would
build four concert halls.

00:05:34.300 --> 00:05:37.230
This is her temple of music at
South Mountain in the Berkshires

00:05:37.230 --> 00:05:39.100
in Pittsfield, Massachusetts.

00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:42.030
She also funded and built
ooze well as the Coolidge,

00:05:42.030 --> 00:05:46.610
the Sprague Music Hall at Yale
and the hall at Mills College.

00:05:46.610 --> 00:05:50.160
Here she is with her very good
friends, the composer Frank Bridge

00:05:50.160 --> 00:05:52.280
and his wife in Pittsfield.

00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:57.560
I couldn't resist this picture
of the Neptune Plaza here

00:05:57.560 --> 00:06:02.440
at the Library to place us visually
here in Washington around 1920.

00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:05.480
Coming to Washington
and creating a new home

00:06:05.480 --> 00:06:09.270 position:56%
for her chamber music festivals here
was a daunting challenge requiring

00:06:09.270 --> 00:06:12.860
all her experience and the
help of two important partners.

00:06:12.860 --> 00:06:15.510
The Librarian of Congress
Herbert Putnam

00:06:15.510 --> 00:06:18.840 position:56%
and Music Division Chief Carl Engel.

00:06:20.270 --> 00:06:23.250
Putnam was the first
professional Librarian of Congress

00:06:23.250 --> 00:06:25.440
and also he was an attorney.

00:06:25.440 --> 00:06:28.900
He was from the Putnam
publishing family.

00:06:28.900 --> 00:06:31.890
Carl Engel, much younger,
born in Paris,

00:06:31.890 --> 00:06:34.700
and educated in Germany
was multilingual,

00:06:34.700 --> 00:06:37.030
cultivated, and very smart.

00:06:37.030 --> 00:06:40.750 position:56%
He had a strong scholarly background
imminently suited to his career

00:06:40.750 --> 00:06:42.530
in a discipline that's
recently begun

00:06:42.530 --> 00:06:46.190
to be known as public musicology.

00:06:46.190 --> 00:06:49.900
This is an image of Carl Engel
with the composer Ernst Bloch.

00:06:49.900 --> 00:06:52.220
And the little cartoon
next to it is interesting.

00:06:52.220 --> 00:06:54.450
It shows, it gives you
a sense of something

00:06:54.450 --> 00:06:56.660
of the relationship he
had with Mrs. Coolidge.

00:06:56.660 --> 00:07:00.910
It refers to the Michelin Tires.

00:07:00.910 --> 00:07:03.810
And the little figure on
the left is called Michel

00:07:03.810 --> 00:07:06.500
and the woman's figure is Lean.

00:07:06.500 --> 00:07:11.230
And it has to do with the pneumatic
tires which keep on going and,

00:07:11.230 --> 00:07:15.220
you know, last forever,
durable, powerful, and so on.

00:07:15.220 --> 00:07:20.310
And there were a lot of inside
jokes between the two of them.

00:07:20.310 --> 00:07:22.060
Their letters are fascinating.

00:07:22.060 --> 00:07:24.330
And if you read her
biography by Cyrilla Barr,

00:07:24.330 --> 00:07:28.110
you really will be engaged.

00:07:28.110 --> 00:07:30.910
Engel's warm relationship
with Mrs. Coolidge was based

00:07:30.910 --> 00:07:33.670
on deep respect, mutual respect.

00:07:33.670 --> 00:07:36.960
They set the artistic bar
very high from the beginning,

00:07:36.960 --> 00:07:40.740
choosing both European and
American composers and performers

00:07:40.740 --> 00:07:43.650
with Mrs. Coolidge
favoring the former.

00:07:43.650 --> 00:07:47.070
My idea of service to America
does not fully embrace the Monroe

00:07:47.070 --> 00:07:50.000
Doctrine, she wrote to him.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:51.300
These two area [inaudible]

00:07:51.300 --> 00:07:53.950
but practical gentlemen
helped her make a foray

00:07:53.950 --> 00:07:56.550
into Washington cultural circles.

00:07:56.550 --> 00:07:58.970
Her three successful
concerts at the Freer Gallery

00:07:58.970 --> 00:08:01.820
in 1924 would open
the door to her goal

00:08:01.820 --> 00:08:06.220
of finding a permanent government
home base for her festivals.

00:08:06.220 --> 00:08:10.780
Briskly moving forward, she
presented an unprecedented idea

00:08:10.780 --> 00:08:15.260
to establish a concert series
within the libraries of Congress.

00:08:15.260 --> 00:08:20.030
Both the librarian and the Congress
had to be persuaded she said later.

00:08:20.030 --> 00:08:23.600
She possessed powerful
skills of persuasion.

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:27.670
In the long run, as the composer
Daniel Gregory Mason said,

00:08:27.670 --> 00:08:30.330
people usually did what
Mrs. Coolidge wanted.

00:08:30.330 --> 00:08:34.630
It would be an unbelievably short
five minutes from her letter

00:08:34.630 --> 00:08:38.960
of intent to the final signature
from President Coolidge.

00:08:38.960 --> 00:08:44.620
This is the bill, and today is
the very day, 90 years to the day,

00:08:44.620 --> 00:08:48.350
that Calvin Coolidge
signed this bill into law.

00:08:48.350 --> 00:08:52.440
Already today, we have talked
about this for an interview

00:08:52.440 --> 00:08:55.440
with St. Lawrence quartet which
is premiering a new work tonight

00:08:55.440 --> 00:08:57.900
in the Washington premier
of a new co-commission

00:08:57.900 --> 00:08:59.740
by John Adams which you'll hear.

00:08:59.740 --> 00:09:04.960
And we talked about this fact and
how exciting it was 90 years today.

00:09:04.960 --> 00:09:08.450
And the resolution
says to accept the gift

00:09:08.450 --> 00:09:11.460
of Elizabeth Sprague Coolidge for
the construction of an auditorium

00:09:11.460 --> 00:09:14.340
in connection with the Library
of Congress and to provide

00:09:14.340 --> 00:09:17.320
for the erection thereof.

00:09:17.320 --> 00:09:21.910
So this is the shot built as you
know right in the courtyard there.

00:09:21.910 --> 00:09:25.420
They simply started
building from the ground up.

00:09:25.420 --> 00:09:28.090
From a techno file viewpoint,

00:09:28.090 --> 00:09:30.730
Mrs. Coolidge was astonishingly
prescient.

00:09:30.730 --> 00:09:34.260
She insisted on engaging a
team of German acousticians

00:09:34.260 --> 00:09:38.460
and on wiring the Coolidge for
the very new medium of radio.

00:09:38.460 --> 00:09:40.320
Thus, the very first
consent was heard

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:44.100
on the radio inaugurating an
astonishing 90 year tradition

00:09:44.100 --> 00:09:46.820
of library broadcasts that
aired across the country

00:09:46.820 --> 00:09:50.420
and developing an appreciation
for chamber music nationwide.

00:09:50.420 --> 00:09:53.890
She believed firmly that
if you could hear the best,

00:09:53.890 --> 00:09:55.620
you would begin to love it.

00:09:55.620 --> 00:09:58.930
And she talked about this in
promoting the radio broadcasts.

00:09:58.930 --> 00:10:03.270
For many decades, ours was the
longest running classical music

00:10:03.270 --> 00:10:04.760
series on the radio.

00:10:04.760 --> 00:10:09.160
So let's hear what Mrs.
Coolidge said herself.

00:10:11.200 --> 00:10:14.240
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Sprague Coolidge:
After some years in Pittsfield,

00:10:14.240 --> 00:10:18.430 position:56%
my chamber music festivals had grown
to such proportions and seem to be

00:10:18.430 --> 00:10:23.330
so important that I decided to
perpetuate them by placing them

00:10:23.330 --> 00:10:26.240
under institutional management.

00:10:26.240 --> 00:10:29.810
Still another chance suggestion
then led me to consider the Library

00:10:29.810 --> 00:10:33.000
of Congress as the most
desirable, personal,

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:37.990
and permanent administrator
of my cherished project.

00:10:37.990 --> 00:10:42.570
Dear Carl Engel and the Library
Mr. Herbert Putnam proved deeply

00:10:42.570 --> 00:10:46.990
sympathetic and enormously
helpful in bringing this about.

00:10:46.990 --> 00:10:49.550
And I was not only
very glad to share

00:10:49.550 --> 00:10:52.380
in that increasingly
heavy responsibility,

00:10:52.380 --> 00:10:55.470
but also welcome the
opportunity to establish

00:10:55.470 --> 00:10:58.890
in the government a little wedge
of authority in matters of art.

00:10:58.890 --> 00:11:02.950
I think I was even kindly accused

00:11:02.950 --> 00:11:06.150
of a little [inaudible]
and, perhaps, justly.

00:11:06.150 --> 00:11:09.530
For I could wish for music the
same governmental protection

00:11:09.530 --> 00:11:14.530
that is given to hygiene,
education, or public welfare.

00:11:14.530 --> 00:11:16.320
How wonderful if we could have

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:20.390
in the cabinet a secretary
of fine arts.

00:11:20.390 --> 00:11:24.780
I feel that in the course of 26
years, my concerts have developed

00:11:24.780 --> 00:11:29.220
and guided my career as
much as I have guided them.

00:11:29.220 --> 00:11:31.950
One idea has evolved another.

00:11:31.950 --> 00:11:34.670
One event has grown into another.

00:11:34.670 --> 00:11:39.740 position:56%
I have followed their direction into
paths at first entirely unforeseen.

00:11:39.740 --> 00:11:42.750
Until today I find
myself in your midst

00:11:42.750 --> 00:11:46.770
at this festival feeling the
radiation of friendship and beauty

00:11:46.770 --> 00:11:51.880
which chamber music broadcasts ooze
I feel the return messages augments

00:11:51.880 --> 00:11:55.750
a thousand fold but center
in this little auditorium

00:11:55.750 --> 00:11:59.120
in the Library of Congress.

00:11:59.120 --> 00:12:04.050
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: It's great to share
these bits of history with you.

00:12:04.050 --> 00:12:06.990
We have a lot of them in our
archives, and over the course

00:12:06.990 --> 00:12:09.160
of the next year, we're
going to be pulling them out

00:12:09.160 --> 00:12:14.910
and broadcasting them, podcasting
them, and making everybody aware

00:12:14.910 --> 00:12:19.140
of a lot of our treasures in
the history of the concerts.

00:12:19.140 --> 00:12:21.410
Many of the famous
musicians who performed here

00:12:21.410 --> 00:12:23.540
in Mrs. Coolidge's day
were her good friends.

00:12:23.540 --> 00:12:25.630
And you got an idea, a little bit,

00:12:25.630 --> 00:12:29.880
from herring her talk what
kind of a person she was.

00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:32.980
She was warm and immensely engaged

00:12:32.980 --> 00:12:35.000
in music making as
a private citizen.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:39.300
She played chamber music with many,
many, many now legendary figures.

00:12:39.300 --> 00:12:41.970
In Europe and in America.

00:12:41.970 --> 00:12:46.960
She came with a great Rolodex
this is the Coolidge Medal

00:12:46.960 --> 00:12:50.400
of Chamber Music that she created
in those early years to award

00:12:50.400 --> 00:12:54.210
to people contributing
significantly to chamber music.

00:12:54.210 --> 00:12:56.620
Benjamin Britain was
an early recipient.

00:12:56.620 --> 00:13:00.630
I thought about that theory
of the great men in history.

00:13:00.630 --> 00:13:04.670 position:56%
The figures like Alexander the
Great, George Washington, and so on.

00:13:04.670 --> 00:13:06.680
People who don't merely
participate in history,

00:13:06.680 --> 00:13:08.380
they make it or chart it somehow.

00:13:08.380 --> 00:13:11.130
And things would have been
very different without them.

00:13:11.130 --> 00:13:14.710
With this highly debatable
idea in mind, it's instructive

00:13:14.710 --> 00:13:17.610
to review some of the prime
movers we've seen here.

00:13:17.610 --> 00:13:21.450
Magisterial interpreters
and great musical thinkers.

00:13:21.450 --> 00:13:24.630
Our concert archives
document their contributions,

00:13:24.630 --> 00:13:28.040 position:56%
trends in composition, and
performance practices, and the shift

00:13:28.040 --> 00:13:31.910
and sway of intellectual
and societal currents.

00:13:31.910 --> 00:13:36.260 position:56%
One such performer was Vondelon
Dovska [phonetic], a harpsichordist,

00:13:36.260 --> 00:13:40.070
the major force in the revival
of early music and a pioneer

00:13:40.070 --> 00:13:42.040
as was Mrs. Coolidge herself

00:13:42.040 --> 00:13:45.150
who would present other
pioneers was Safford Cape,

00:13:45.150 --> 00:13:47.510
Noah Greenberg, and Alfred Deller.

00:13:47.510 --> 00:13:51.590
She also underwrote substantial
musicological research.

00:13:51.590 --> 00:13:55.170
She was a champion of the very,
very old as well as the very new.

00:13:55.170 --> 00:14:00.840
The famous Hampton Institute
Choir appeared here in 1926

00:14:00.840 --> 00:14:04.530
with the composer R
Nathaniel Dett as conductor.

00:14:04.530 --> 00:14:06.170
Their program was striking.

00:14:06.170 --> 00:14:09.880
Renaissance music, Russian
liturgical music, French songs,

00:14:09.880 --> 00:14:15.540
and spirituals described in that
program as Negro folk anthems.

00:14:15.540 --> 00:14:17.970
Carl Engel had offered
Dett a commission

00:14:17.970 --> 00:14:21.970 position:56%
from the Coolidge foundation
suggesting a work for violin, piano,

00:14:21.970 --> 00:14:24.800
saxophone, and banjo with a thought

00:14:24.800 --> 00:14:28.730
to bring together European
tradition with American influence.

00:14:28.730 --> 00:14:31.580
Dett returned a dignified
letter saying, quote,

00:14:31.580 --> 00:14:36.020
any effort from the outside to
lay down rather strict lines along

00:14:36.020 --> 00:14:40.560
which art should develop can only
result in self consciousness and,

00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:45.010
consequently, in artistic
and in sincere results.

00:14:45.010 --> 00:14:49.400
The 1928 Coolidge Commission

00:14:49.400 --> 00:14:53.370 position:56%
for [inaudible] brought together the
Russian-born choreographer Adolph

00:14:53.370 --> 00:14:56.780
Bolm with Igor Stravinsky
as the composer.

