And it's charming because he talks
about, again, it's like a view

00:45:17.140 --> 00:45:20.350
into the past through the
viewfinder of a kaleidoscope.

00:45:20.350 --> 00:45:22.050
But back to Nadia Boulanger.

00:45:22.050 --> 00:45:26.510 position:56%
He talks about how in the books he
says everyone thinks I went to Paris

00:45:26.510 --> 00:45:29.440
to study Nadia Boulanger,
I didn't know who she was.

00:45:29.440 --> 00:45:32.820
And he said I didn't
want to tell my folks

00:45:32.820 --> 00:45:34.360
that I was studying with a woman.

00:45:34.360 --> 00:45:36.760
I'm paraphrasing, but
it's very funny.

00:45:36.760 --> 00:45:38.060
And he has the instincts

00:45:38.060 --> 00:45:40.240
of a comedian while
he's doing all of this.

00:45:40.240 --> 00:45:46.080
So I raise Copeland because, again,
it underscores one of the themes

00:45:46.080 --> 00:45:49.880
of my talk which is relationships
throughout these many years we've

00:45:49.880 --> 00:45:51.180
been in business.

00:45:51.180 --> 00:45:55.570
And we want to honor the
Copeland/Graham relationship

00:45:55.570 --> 00:46:01.060
and the path breaking
ballet that they created.

00:46:01.060 --> 00:46:07.360
We will be mounting [inaudible]
Spring again April next year.

00:46:07.360 --> 00:46:10.770
And the Martha Graham Company
will be here for two days.

00:46:10.770 --> 00:46:14.350
But we will also have a
brand new dance commission.

00:46:14.350 --> 00:46:15.960 position:56%
I can't say too much more than that,

00:46:15.960 --> 00:46:20.040
but we're putting the final touches
now to some contracts and so on.

00:46:20.040 --> 00:46:23.060
So it's very exciting.

00:46:23.060 --> 00:46:31.160
I'll just say in wrapping this
up that I asked someone last week

00:46:31.160 --> 00:46:35.360
to give me a two word response to
the idea of the Library series.

00:46:35.360 --> 00:46:39.470
And she said venerable
and adventurous.

00:46:40.610 --> 00:46:44.470
We want to in this coming 90
weeks honor Mrs. Coolidge's

00:46:44.470 --> 00:46:46.190
adventurous spirit.

00:46:46.190 --> 00:46:49.750
One of the most fun things I know
about her is that she spent a lot

00:46:49.750 --> 00:46:52.690
of time in 1920s trying
to find a way

00:46:52.690 --> 00:46:56.480
to bring a [inaudible]
orchestra to the Coolidge.

00:46:58.260 --> 00:47:02.500
Time and space are on their
last legs, I think, she said.

00:47:02.500 --> 00:47:06.850
This is a fascinating comment
in the pre-Internet age.

00:47:06.850 --> 00:47:10.500
And we shall all have
to re-educate our senses

00:47:10.500 --> 00:47:14.880
to interpret a new set
of sensory impressions.

00:47:16.690 --> 00:47:20.870
Today, as I said, she would
be called a visionary.

00:47:20.870 --> 00:47:29.600
She remains startlingly focused
example of someone with instincts

00:47:29.600 --> 00:47:32.010
for presenting great art.

00:47:32.010 --> 00:47:35.120
She stated her goal
as, quote, to serve art

00:47:35.120 --> 00:47:37.680
and through art to serve humanity.

00:47:37.680 --> 00:47:41.270
Following with, quote, the survival

00:47:41.270 --> 00:47:46.220
of the human spirit largely
depends upon its artistic freedom.

00:47:46.220 --> 00:47:50.270
Pointing it especially
in the past month.

00:47:50.270 --> 00:47:54.180
Music is a mechanism
to approach the divine.

00:47:54.180 --> 00:47:56.710
This is a statement
I noted down once

00:47:56.710 --> 00:47:58.460
but have never found the source.

00:47:58.460 --> 00:48:02.320
If you know it or can
find it, let me know.

00:48:02.320 --> 00:48:06.300
However one might define
the concept of the divine,

00:48:06.300 --> 00:48:09.680
I know that as presenters
and audience members,

00:48:09.680 --> 00:48:13.940
we share in making
this approach together.

00:48:13.940 --> 00:48:15.850
We look forward tremendously

00:48:15.850 --> 00:48:20.510
to celebrating the Library's
90th anniversary with you.

00:48:20.510 --> 00:48:25.650
[ Applause ]

